      "frey-curve": {
        "title": "The Frey curve",
        "questions": [
          {
            "type": "mcq",
            "q": "Let $a,b,c$ be a hypothetical coprime solution of $a^p + b^p = c^p$ with $p \\ge 5$ prime. The Frey curve $E_{a,b,c}: y^2 = x(x-a^p)(x+b^p)$ has discriminant equal to which of the following?",
            "choices": [
              "$\\Delta = (abc)^{2p}/2^{8}$",
              "$\\Delta = (abc)^{p}$",
              "$\\Delta = a^p b^p c^p$",
              "$\\Delta = 2^{8}(abc)^{2p}$"
            ],
            "answer": 0,
            "explain": "For $y^2 = x(x-\\alpha)(x+\\beta)$ with $\\gamma = \\alpha+\\beta$, the discriminant is $16(\\alpha\\beta\\gamma)^2$. With $\\alpha=a^p,\\beta=b^p,\\gamma=c^p$ this gives $16\\,(a b c)^{2p}$; after the standard change of variables to minimal model the factor of $2^{8}$ drops out, leaving $\\Delta = (abc)^{2p}/2^{8}$."
          },
          {
            "type": "numeric",
            "q": "Evaluate $\\log_{10}\\Delta$ for the <em>formal</em> Frey discriminant $\\Delta = (abc)^{2p}/2^{8}$ with $a=3,\\ b=4,\\ c=5,\\ p=5$. (No integer $c$ exists with $3^5+4^5=c^5$ — this is a sanity check on the formula only.) Round to 2 decimals.",
            "answer": 15.37,
            "tol": 0.05,
            "explain": "$abc = 60$, so $(abc)^{2p} = 60^{10}$. $\\log_{10}(60^{10}) = 10\\log_{10}60 \\approx 10\\cdot 1.7782 = 17.782$. Subtract $\\log_{10}2^{8} = 8\\log_{10}2 \\approx 2.408$: $17.782-2.408 \\approx 15.37$."
          },
          {
            "type": "mcq",
            "q": "The prime factorization of the Frey discriminant is a perfect $2p$-th power away from $2$. This forces the Frey curve to be:",
            "choices": [
              "supersingular at every prime",
              "semistable (multiplicative reduction at every odd prime dividing $abc$)",
              "isogenous to $y^2 = x^3 - x$",
              "ramified at every prime"
            ],
            "answer": 1,
            "explain": "A prime $\\ell \\mid abc$ with $\\ell$ odd appears in $\\Delta$ to multiplicity $2p$, i.e. a perfect square. By Tate's algorithm this gives multiplicative reduction, so the curve is semistable; the conductor $N_E$ is squarefree away from $2$."
          }
        ]
      },
